document_data.Defenses:
During the wars between Thay and Mulhorand, the pass of Thazar was used as an eastern approach to Thay.{{cite book/Pirates of the Fallen Stars|5}} Privateers from Murghom were a constant threat to [[Dhaztanar]] around the same time.{{cite book/The Horde/Volume I|414}}

Murghôm was too poorly administered to combat the bandits in the Mountains of Copper, and thus limited itself to patrolling the most traveled roads.{{cite book/The Horde/Volume II|85}} Zindalankh was under the protection of the Bey of Murghôm, but the citizens paid little mind to his laws.{{cite book/The Horde/Volume II|109}} Mercenaries in the service of king [[Tharmakkas IV]] viewed the soldiers stationed at [[Port Ghaast]] as pompous, unprofessional fools. They were neither very motivated nor highly trained.{{cite book/The Horde/Volume II|94}}

Under the rule of the dragon princes of Murghôm, the nation issued permits for mercenary companies of 40 or fewer veterans. All were formed by former Murghômi commanders as the nation's armed forces were reduced by the dragon princes' decrees over the decades. Murghômi mercenary companies were forbidden from banding together while on the nation's lands or its immediate neighbors, like Thay. In the 15{{th}} century DR, some of the noteworthy mercenary companies were [[Naelor's Banner]], based out of [[Nimjammir]], [[Shaele's Shields]], based out of [[Vurlakh]] under the command of [[Shaele Flamehair]], and [[Turvuld's Swords]] in [[Sessim]].{{Cite web/theedverse/2023-01-07 - Murghôm Mercenary Companies}}

document_data.Government:
During the age of ancient [[Netheril]], Murghôm was thought to have been ruled by the family of the then mortal [[Myrkul]], known at the time as Myrkul Bey al-Kursi, the Crown Prince of Murghôm.<ref>{{Cite dungeon/170/Monument of the Ancients|80}}

Before the 15{{th}} century, the leaders of the Murghômi were called [[ataman]]s. The state was a series of semi-autonomous communities that gathered into collective government only in times of war.

That changed in the 15{{th}} century DR, when Murghôm was "conquered" by dragons. As of [[1489 DR]], the nation was ruled by the powerful [[Princes of Murghôm|dragon princes]].

document_data.History:
A local peak in the Mountains of Copper, called [[The Kobold Crown]], was thought to have held a [[kobold]] civilization once, annihilated by {{yearlink|1368}}.{{Cite dragon/216/Elminster's Notebook: Kobold commotions}} The ancient city of [[Dharrmaghongh]] in Murghom was leveled by a single ''[[rune of power]]'' in ancient times.{{cite book/Dwarves Deep|42}}

Mulhorand used to encompass Murghôm{{cite book/Unapproachable East|188}} from its annexation{{cite book/Races of Faerun|95}} in {{yearlink|-1500}}.{{cite book/The Grand History of the Realms|36}}

The [[Daggers of Dusk]] were known to have meddled in the affairs of Murghôm after the fall of the [[Shoon Dynasty]], for a bit longer after {{yearlink|450}}.{{cite web/Realmslore/The Purple Halls}}

The [[Havi]] attacks on Murghôm after the independence of Semphar greatly contributed to diminishing the Mulhorandi control of the area.{{cite book/The Horde/Volume I|19}}
Though Murghom was declared a vassal state once Mulhorand expanded again, their hold was tenuous, and Murghom declared itself independent after Semphar did. It remained effectively a vassal state of [[Mulhorand]], however.{{cite book/Power of Faerun|90}}

Murghôm had a rivalry with Semphar, and had militarily disputed many territories between the rivers Ghaast and Haqar. There had been two wars in which Murghôm attempted to reclaim Semphar. It was semi-independent from Mulhorand, but would provide food or soldiers upon request. As of 1357, it hadn't been requested in centuries. Most of the incarnations of Mulhorand saw Murghôm as a land with no ties to them whatsoever.

During the wars between Thay and Mulhorand, the pass of Thazar was used as an eastern approach to Thay.{{cite book/The Grand History of the Realms|130}} In the {{yearlinkName|1320}}, the forces [[Thay]] ravaged Murghôm in their invasion of Mulhorand.{{cite book/Unapproachable East|163}}

Per [[Elminster Aumar]], the brothers [[Iraun]] and [[Srivven]] hailed from a mage academy in east Murghôm, which was destroyed in a conflict between students and mentors. The event must have happened well before the {{yearlinkName|1353}}, when the brothers' stay at [[Adaerglast]] was known to the Mage Royal of [[Zindalankh]].{{Cite polyhedron/135/Elminster's Everwinking Eye: A Wayfarers Guide to the Forgotten Realms|8}}

A group of escapees from [[Mulhorand]] and [[Thay]] who hid in the [[Ganathwood]] around {{yearlink|1367}} had been at least partly destroyed after attacking a Murghômi village in {{yearlink|1369}} by the druids [[Berun]] and [[Chereth]].{{cite book/Sentinelspire|18|2}}

document_data.Culture:
Mulhorandi was spoken in Murghôm. Curses and spells to safeguard tombs were favored in the area.{{cite book/Races of Faerun|96}} Along with the [[Mulhorandi]], the Murghômi spoke [[Mulhorandi (language)|Mulhorandi]] and revered the [[Mulhorandi pantheon]]{{cite book/The Horde/Volume I|17}}

Murghôm worshipped the Mulhorandi pantheon;{{cite book/Races of Faerun|98}} Thoth was considered the protector of Murghôm.{{cite book/Old Empires|26}} Though Thoth held the title of Protector of Murghôm, he had little interest in the land, as it held little interest in mages.{{cite book/Powers and Pantheons|130}} By 1371 DR, the Mulhorandi pantheon's flock was dwindling in Murghôm,{{cite book/Powers and Pantheons|94, 96}} and there were only some temples in some isolated parts of the realm.{{cite book/Powers and Pantheons|131}} It was widely hypothesized that at least one great temple of [[Silvanus]] existed in the great wild wood of Murghôm.{{Cite dragon/412/Channel Divinity: Chauntea and Silvanus|24}}

The highly-valued{{cite book/Races of Faerun|98}} horse breeds of Murghôm descended from Raurin horses; Semphari horses were bred in Murghôm,{{cite book/Champions of Valor|156}} found mainly between that realm and Semphar. The Murghômi were known for their skill with horses.{{cite web/Candlekeep Forum/Questions for Ed Greenwood (2008)/12-05 - Horse Riding in the Realms}}

Giant sturgeon were considered a delicacy in the courts of Murghôm, and the fish were paid for handsomely.{{cite book/The Horde/Volume II|107}}

document_data.Trade and Industry:
Its copper was traded with the nomads in [[Ejen Horo]].{{cite book/The Horde/Volume II|76}} Rugs from Murghôm were traded far and wide. The [[Rauthenflow]] river was central to trade in Murghôm, and several dredging barges were used to keep it navigable.{{cite book/The Horde/Volume II|103}} 

Murghômi traders who sought to trade with Rashemen had to go through [[Shevel]]. Travelers from [[Thay]] headed for Murghôm took the road south from [[Pyarados]] to [[Rauthil]] in the mid-late 14{{th}} century [[DR]].{{cite book/Unapproachable East|155}} Traders trying to avoid the taxes of Murghôm would sometimes cut through the Spice Road.{{cite book/The Horde/Volume II|105}}

There had been a printing industry for approximately three hundred years as of the mid-late 14{{th}} century DR.{{cite web/Candlekeep Forum/Questions for Ed Greenwood (2007)/02-21 - Printing in the Realms}} The term for a tannery was "batar" as of {{yearlink|1372}}. The same word was used in Semphar.{{cite web/The Border Kingdoms/Gallard}} [[Kukri]] were popular in Murghôm.{{cite web/theedverse/2020-04-19 - Kukri}} A local industry made cheap boxes for import.{{cite web/Candlekeep Forum/Questions for Ed Greenwood (2008)/2007/12-31 - Haedrul Marlsword}}

[[Elkammath]] tea was brewed from the fibrous roots of groundnuts found in Murghôm, its neighboring regions, and Chondath.{{cite web/theedverse/2018-08-25 - Tea in the Realms}} [[Halva]] from Murghôm was made with hard honeycomb.{{Cite web/theedverse/2021-07-30 - Halva}} [[Marka]] was made from a bush that grew in local foothills.{{Cite web/theedverse/2021-04-13 - Arispeg, Delph, and Marka}} Ring-shaped loaves were a known food, measuring at least 10 inches in width, with some far larger.{{cite web/Candlekeep Forum/Questions for Ed Greenwood (2010)/07-05 Ring-shaped Pastries}}

In the mid-14{{th}} century [[DR]], Murghôm had a small silk industry, though it was inferior to [[Shou]] production.{{cite web/Candlekeep Forum/Questions for Ed Greenwood (2012)/03-21 Silk trade in the Realms}} There were also some traders in the late 14{{th}} century DR who had attempted to raise [[korontaun]], though the goats struggled in the climate.{{cite web/Candlekeep Forum/Questions for Ed Greenwood (2009)/03-03 Korontaun}}

